<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">

<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>
        <%= title %> | Forecasting Recessions
    </title>
    <link rel="stylesheet" href="/css/style.css">
</head>

<body>
    <%- include('partials/header') %>

        <main>
            <h1>Major Findings</h1>
            <section>
                <h2>1. Analysis Findings</h2>
                <p>During the exploratory data analysis (EDA) phase, we observed that no single economic indicator
                    follows a consistent pattern before every recession. Each historical U.S. recession was triggered by
                    different factors — from oil shocks and aggressive Fed tightening to housing bubbles and a global
                    pandemic. Because of this, rather than looking for one universal warning sign, we compared the
                    current
                    data (April 2024 – March 2026) for each of the six indicators against every pre-recession period
                    across
                    six time windows to determine which past recession today's economy most closely resembles.</p>
                <p>
                    In comparison to the current economic conditions (2024-2026), we have excluded the inflation data.
                    This
                    is because the inflation data is only updated yearly and not available for 2025 onwards.
                </p>

                <h3>1.1 Indicator Changes Before Each Recession</h3>
                <p>Based on the historical percentage changes of each indicator leading up to past recessions, we
                    observed the following trends:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Unemployment & Inflation:</strong> Unemployment typically rises after a recession begins
                        rather than before, making it a weak early warning indicator. Inflation shows a mixed pattern
                        with no consistent direction.</li>
                    <li><strong>Interest Rates:</strong> The behavior of interest rates varies across different periods,
                        largely because they reflect central bank policy responses rather than direct economic stress.
                    </li>
                    <li><strong>Market-Based Indicators (S&P 500 & VIX):</strong> Market indicators often provide
                        earlier signals than macroeconomic variables. The S&P 500 typically begins to decline 3 to 6
                        months before a recession, while the VIX volatility index spikes sharply as a recession
                        approaches.</li>
                    <li><strong>Commodities (Gold & Oil):</strong> Both gold and oil prices fail to show a consistent
                        pattern across historical recessions.</li>
                </ul>

                <div class="content-grid">
                    <figure>
                        <img src="/images/EDA/indicators%20changes%20heatmap%201970.png" alt="Indicator heatmap 1968">
                        <figcaption>Figure 1. Indicator percentage changes before recessions (1968–2024).</figcaption>
                    </figure>
                    <figure>
                        <img src="/images/EDA/indicator%20changes%20heatmap%201990.png" alt="Indicator heatmap 1990">
                        <figcaption>Figure 2. Indicator percentage changes before recessions (1990–2024).</figcaption>
                    </figure>
                </div>

                <p>Overall, these results suggest that while market-based indicators react faster and provide earlier
                    warnings, recession patterns ultimately depend on the specific underlying causes of each economic
                    downturn.</p>
                <br>

                <h3>1.1 Overall Recession Similarity Ranking</h3>
                <p>
                    In compare current economic data (2024 - 2026) to past pre-recession periods,we have used two
                    methods: Spearman correlation and Dynamic Time Warping (DTW).
                </p>
                <table class="table">
                    <thead>
                        <tr>
                            <th></th>
                            <th>Spearman</th>
                            <th>Dynamic Time Wraping (DTW)</th>
                        </tr>
                    </thead>
                    <tbody>
                        <tr>
                            <td>Measurement focus</td>
                            <td>Directional alignment of trends at each point in time</td>
                            <td>Overall similarity in the shape of trends over time</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <td>Score interpretation</td>
                            <td>Higher values indicate stronger synchronization in movement</td>
                            <td>Higher values indicate stronger similarity in pattern, regardless of timing</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <td>Analytical insight</td>
                            <td>Assesses whether current conditions are evolving in line with past periods</td>
                            <td>Assesses whether current dynamics structurally resemble past cycles</td>
                        </tr>
                    </tbody>
                </table>

                <p>The two bar graphs below rank all eight recessions by their average similarity score across all
                    <strong>six indicators</strong> and all <strong>six time windows</strong>.
                </p>

                <figure>
                    <img src="/images/Major%20findings/Overall-Recession-similarity.png"
                        alt="Overall Recession Similarity Ranking">
                    <figcaption>Figure 3. Overall Recession Similarity Ranking.</figcaption>
                </figure>

                <p>Two recessions stand out as statistically notable matches to the current economic environment:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>2008</strong> is the clearest match to today, with the highest similarity in both
                        measures, followed by <strong>2020</strong> as the second closest.</li>
                    <li>Most other recessions show only moderate similarity (scores mostly between 40–59), meaning
                        today’s conditions are not strongly aligned with them.</li>
                    <li>DTW scores are consistently higher than Spearman, suggesting the overall patterns/trends look
                        similar, even if the exact relationships between indicators are weaker.</li>
                </ul>
            </section>

            <section>
                <h2>2. Machine Learning Findings</h2>

                <h3>2.1 Model Comparison</h3>
                <p>We compared two approaches for recession prediction: <strong>Logistic Regression</strong> (linear
                    model) and
                    <strong>Random Forest</strong> (non-linear model).
                </p>

                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Logistic Regression</strong> produces smooth, stable probability signals and provides
                        consistent early warnings.</li>
                    <li><strong>Random Forest</strong> captures more complex patterns but produces unstable predictions,
                        often either missing recessions or generating false alarms.</li>
                </ul>

                <h3>2.2 Performance Summary</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Logistic Regression</strong> shows the best overall balance between precision and
                        recall, making it reliable for early-warning detection.</li>
                    <li><strong>Random Forest</strong> is inconsistent:
                        <ul>
                            <li>Some models are too conservative (miss recessions)</li>
                            <li>Others are too sensitive (many false alarms)</li>
                            <li>The combined model shows perfect results, indicating likely <strong>overfitting</strong>
                                due to limited recession data</li>
                        </ul>
                    </li>
                </ul>

                <div class="content-grid">
                    <figure>
                        <img src="/images/ML/LR-confusion-matrix.png" alt="Logistic Regression Confusion Matrix">
                        <figcaption>Figure 4. Logistic Regression Confusion Matrix.</figcaption>
                    </figure>
                    <figure>
                        <img src="/images/ML/RF-confusion-matrix.png" alt="Random Forest Confusion Matrix">
                        <figcaption>Figure 5. Random Forest Confusion Matrix.</figcaption>
                    </figure>
                </div>

                <h3>2.3 Feature Insights</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Macro indicators</strong> provide the most stable and reliable signals.</li>
                    <li><strong>Financial indicators</strong> react faster but are more volatile and noisy.</li>
                    <li>The best-performing setup is <strong>Macro + S&amp;P 500 (Model D)</strong>, balancing stability
                        and responsiveness.</li>
                </ul>

                <h3>2.4 Conclusion</h3>
                <p>
                    Overall, <strong>Logistic Regression outperforms Random Forest</strong> for this task. It delivers
                    more
                    consistent, interpretable, and reliable early-warning signals. While Random Forest can model complex
                    relationships, it struggles with limited recession data and is more prone to instability and
                    overfitting.
                </p>

                <p><strong>Key takeaway:</strong> Simpler models perform better when data is limited and stability is
                    critical for
                    early recession detection.</p>
            </section>

            <section>
                <h2>3. Final Conclusion</h2>
                <p>Across all indicators and time windows analyzed, the <strong>current economic environment
                        (2024–2026)</strong> most
                    consistently resembles the period leading up to the <strong>2008 Great Recession</strong>, with the
                    <strong>2020 COVID
                        Pandemic</strong>
                    emerging as a secondary analogue. This alignment is not driven by any single metric but is
                    reinforced
                    across multiple indicators, notably in gold, interest rates, and equity markets.
                    While unemployment remains moderate and oil prices subdued, the convergence of signals across the
                    remaining indicators warrants serious attention. History does not repeat perfectly, but the patterns
                    observed here is difficult to dismiss. <strong>The data does not predict a recession with
                        certainty, but the signals are strong enough that they should not be ignored.</strong>
                </p>
            </section>
        </main>

        <%- include('partials/footer') %>
</body>

</html>